Since his day, when roots were to be expressed by radical signs, instead of by the number itself evolved, the expedient devised was to retain the contracted R, as the initial of the word root, and to place within it a small numeral, as the index of the quality of the root. Thus 4710 expresses the cube root, or, as Napier would have called it, the tripartient or third root, of the number ten considered as a radicatum or power. This notae tion‚——which‚ it will be observed, gets rid of the unwieldy expedient of repeating the initials 42, ⁸8, and st, for square, cube, and supersolid, and presents to the eye the number of evolutions requisite to obtain the particular root‚—was not invented until many years after Napier’s death.
